article.description:
Katie Douglas scored 16 of her 21
points in the second half, and Lindsay Whalen scored five points in the last two minutes, leading the Connecticut Sun to a 71-64 win over the slumping Seattle Storm on Sunday.
article.headline: Sun spoil Bird's return to Connecticut
article.linkText: Sun back on top of East after weathering Storm, Bird
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- The Connecticut Sun spoiled Sue Bird's
return and pulled into first place in the process.

Bird had nine points, seven assists and five rebounds in front
of her former hometown fans, but the slumping Seattle Storm
couldn't slow down the Sun, who won their third straight Sunday
with a 71-64 victory and pulled into a first-place tie with the
Charlotte Sting in the Eastern Conference.

The Sun and Sting meet Wednesday in Charlotte in what could be a
showdown for the conference title.

Katie Douglas scored 16 of her 21 points in the second half and
Lindsay Whalen tacked on five of her six points in the final 1:38
to lead Connecticut.

"We still have three Eastern Conference games left, but we have
momentum," Sun forward Nykesha Sales said. "We're depending on
ourselves and nobody else. We've got three games left, and they're
all important."

The Sun own the head-to-head tiebreakers against every team
except Charlotte, and can take that one on Wednesday. Connecticut
then returns home and closes the regular season with games against
the New York Liberty and Indiana Fever.

Lauren Jackson led Seattle (18-13) with a game-high 24 points,
scoring 16 in the first half.

"Lauren Jackson is not going to outscore teams herself," Storm
coach Anne Donovan said. "Other than Alicia Thompson getting nine
points late in the game, we don't have anybody else stepping up."

The Storm lost for the fifth time in six games since the WNBA
returned from the monthlong Olympic break.

Seattle could have clinched a playoff berth with a win. The
Storm remain on the road and face the Indiana Fever on Monday
night, then close with two home games against the Phoenix Mercury
and Los Angeles Sparks.

The Storm lost five in a row near the end of last season and
missed qualifying for the playoffs by a half-game.

"We don't have much time left," Bird said. "There is nothing
really to be said or to be done. We have a game in 24 hours."

Taj McWilliams-Franklin finished with a double-double for the
Sun, scoring 17 points and pulling down 10 rebounds. Sales finished
with 10 points despite a rough 4-for-15 shooting performance, but
she also tied a career high with six steals and added five assists
and five rebounds.

The Sun led by as many as 10 points in the first half, but
closed the half with four turnovers and a missed shot in the final
five possessions to allow Seattle to cut the deficit to 32-28 at
the break.

The Sun lead dropped to three points in the opening minute of
the second half, but Douglas scored eight of Connecticut's next 13
points to help her team pull away by as many as 12 points down the
stretch to secure the win.

"Katie Douglas came to play," Donovan said. "She was really
focused. She is a mature player that waits for an opportunity. She
doesn't try to force the action and she made us pay."
